1	088132e5-f6bd-4124-a5ce-f1705be36e9a	0	{"scope": "Rental housing market in the Netherlands", "subject": "Municipalities (gemeenten); landlords (verhuurders) as regulated parties", "norm_type": "competence", "conditions": "Following the results of the good landlordship pilots", "promulgation": "Minister van Binnenlandse Zaken en Koninkrijksrelaties (Ollongren)", "act_identifier": "", "legal_modality": "can", "norm_identifier": "signal-verhuurdervergunning-2021-02"}	7	general	\N	2026-05-17 18:48:01.601189	Reasoning:\n\n**1. norm_identifier**: This concerns a signal about a bill introducing landlord licensing and uniform standards — I'll use "signal-verhuurdervergunning-2021-02".\n\n**2. norm_type**: The minister announces a bill that will introduce a *bevoegdheid* (power/authority) for municipalities to impose uniform requirements on landlords and to introduce a landlord licence. This is a **competence** norm — it creates a legal power for municipalities. However, it also implies a conduct norm for landlords (they must comply with the requirements and hold a licence). The primary signal here is the creation of a new legal power for municipalities, so **competence** is most appropriate.\n\n**3. promulgation**: The letter is from the Minister of Binnenlandse Zaken en Koninkrijksrelaties. The name is not explicitly stated in this chunk, but in 2021 this was Minister Kajsa Ollongren.\n\n**4. scope**: Housing rental market in the Netherlands; specifically the regulation of landlord conduct and municipal enforcement powers.\n\n**5. conditions**: The bill arises from the results of pilots ("geven de resultaten van de pilots aanleiding om met een wetsvoorstel te komen"). No specific entry-into-force date is stated.\n\n**6. subject**: Municipalities (receiving the competence to impose requirements and issue licences); landlords (verhuurders) as the regulated party.\n\n**7. legal_modality**: The bill introduces a *bevoegdheid* (power) for municipalities — this is **can** (competence/enablement). Municipalities will be enabled to impose requirements and introduce a landlord licence.\n\n**8. act_identifier**: No formal act name is given in this chunk; it is referred to only as "een wetsvoorstel."\n\n**signal_certainty**: The minister says "geven de resultaten van de pilots aanleiding om met een wetsvoorstel te komen" — this is a concrete announcement of an upcoming bill, so **proposed**.\n\n**source_type**: The norm is grounded in a forthcoming bill — **statutory**.\n\n```json\n{\n  "signal_summary": "The Minister of Interior Affairs announces a bill that will give municipalities the power to impose nationally uniform requirements on landlords and to introduce a landlord licensing system, in order to combat rogue landlords.",\n  "signal_certainty": "proposed",\n  "source_type": "statutory",\n  "norm_identifier": "signal-verhuurdervergunning-2021-02",\n  "norm_type": "competence",\n  "promulgation": "Minister van Binnenlandse Zaken en Koninkrijksrelaties (Ollongren)",\n  "scope": "Rental housing market in the Netherlands",\n  "conditions": "Following the results of the good landlordship pilots",\n  "subject": "Municipalities (gemeenten); landlords (verhuurders) as regulated parties",\n  "legal_modality": "can",\n  "act_identifier": ""\n}	The Minister of Interior Affairs announces a bill that will give municipalities the power to impose nationally uniform requirements on landlords and to introduce a landlord licensing system, in order to combat rogue landlords.	proposed	statutory	3693	692
2	f072ca19-05b9-4af1-a895-d5020876fe78	0	{"scope": "Dutch pension system (arbeidsvoorwaardelijke pensioenen) and AOW", "subject": "Pension funds, employers, employees, and self-employed workers (zelfstandigen)", "norm_type": "conduct", "conditions": "Subject to ratification by the social partners' constituencies (achterbannen)", "promulgation": "Minister van Sociale Zaken en Werkgelegenheid", "act_identifier": "", "legal_modality": "ought", "norm_identifier": "signal-pensioenakkoord-2019-06"}	7	general	\N	2026-05-17 18:48:14.400106	Reasoning:\n\n**1. What is the chunk about?**\nThis is an introductory letter from the Minister of Social Affairs and Employment to the Tweede Kamer, announcing that the cabinet, employee organisations, and employer organisations have reached a "principeakkoord" (framework agreement) on the renewal of the pension system, a slower rise in the AOW retirement age, disability insurance for self-employed workers, and measures to enable everyone to reach retirement in good health. The second part describes the problems with the current pension system (rising life expectancy, changing labour market, low interest rates, redistribution effects, lack of indexation, etc.).\n\n**2. Is there a normative signal?**\nYes — the announcement of a "principeakkoord" about the renewal of the pension system is a normative signal. It signals an intention/commitment to reform the pension system. However, it is a framework agreement ("principeakkoord"), not yet a formal legislative proposal or adopted law. The social partners still need to present it to their constituencies ("achterbannen").\n\n**3. Norm type?**\nThe reform of the pension system will create new rules governing pension accrual, contributions, and related matters — these are conduct norms. The primary signal here is about the intention to reform the system, which will impose new obligations on pension funds, employers, and employees. I'll classify this as a conduct norm.\n\n**4. Legal modality?**\nThe agreement signals that the pension system *ought* to be renewed — obligations will be imposed on relevant parties. The modality is "ought."\n\n**5. Promulgation?**\nThe Minister of Social Affairs and Employment (Wouter Koolmees, though not named in this chunk — the letter is signed by the minister but the name is not stated in this excerpt).\n\n**6. Scope?**\nThe Dutch pension system (arbeidsvoorwaardelijke pensioenen) and AOW.\n\n**7. Conditions?**\nSubject to ratification by the social partners' constituencies ("achterbannen").\n\n**8. Subject?**\nPension funds, employers, employees, and self-employed workers (given the mention of disability insurance for zelfstandigen).\n\n**9. Signal certainty?**\n"Proposed" — a principeakkoord has been reached but it still needs to be ratified by the social partners' constituencies and translated into legislation. It is more than advisory but not yet committed.\n\n**10. Source type?**\n"Policy_intent" — this is a framework agreement announced in a policy letter, not yet grounded in legislation.\n\n**11. Act identifier?**\nNo specific act is named.\n\n```json\n{\n  "signal_summary": "The Dutch cabinet and social partners have reached a framework agreement (principeakkoord) to renew the pension system, slow the rise of the AOW retirement age, and introduce disability insurance for self-employed workers, though the agreement still needs ratification by the social partners' constituencies.",\n  "signal_certainty": "proposed",\n  "source_type": "policy_intent",\n  "norm_identifier": "signal-pensioenakkoord-2019-06",\n  "norm_type": "conduct",\n  "promulgation": "Minister van Sociale Zaken en Werkgelegenheid",\n  "scope": "Dutch pension system (arbeidsvoorwaardelijke pensioenen) and AOW",\n  "conditions": "Subject to ratification by the social partners' constituencies (achterbannen)",\n  "subject": "Pension funds, employers, employees, and self-employed workers (zelfstandigen)",\n  "legal_modality": "ought",\n  "act_identifier": ""\n}	The Dutch cabinet and social partners have reached a framework agreement (principeakkoord) to renew the pension system, slow the rise of the AOW retirement age, and introduce disability insurance for self-employed workers, though the agreement still needs ratification by the social partners' constituencies.	proposed	policy_intent	3649	829
3	088132e5-f6bd-4124-a5ce-f1705be36e9a	1	{"scope": "Rental housing market in the Netherlands; municipal enforcement against malicious landlords", "subject": "Gemeenten (municipalities) and verhuurders (landlords)", "norm_type": "competence", "conditions": "Subject to the design and adoption of a possible statutory legal basis (mogelijke wettelijke grondslag)", "promulgation": "Minister van Binnenlandse Zaken en Koninkrijksrelaties (Ollongren)", "act_identifier": "", "legal_modality": "can", "norm_identifier": "signal-verhuurdervergunning-wettelijke-grondslag-2021"}	7	general	\N	2026-05-17 18:48:19.199907	Reasoning:\n\n**Step 1: Identify the normative signal**\nThe chunk describes the results of pilots on "goed verhuurderschap" (good landlordship) and insights gained for tackling malicious landlords ("malafide verhuurders"). It mentions that various cities have developed practices, dashboards, tenant teams, and municipal licensing systems for rental housing. It also references the "beheerovername" (management takeover) instrument under the Woningwet.\n\nThe key normative signal is embedded in the phrase: "maar ook voor het ontwerpen van een mogelijke wettelijke grondslag voor de aanpak van malafide verhuurders" — this signals that the pilot insights are being used to design a possible legal basis for tackling malicious landlords. This is a forward-looking policy intent, not yet a formal proposal.\n\n**Step 2: norm_type**\nThe text describes a policy process leading toward a possible statutory instrument (wettelijke grondslag) for a landlord licensing system. This would create a competence/regulatory framework — but the signal here is more about the conduct norm that would result (landlords would need a permit). However, since the text is primarily about designing a legal basis (wettelijke grondslag) for a licensing system (vergunningsstelsel), this leans toward a competence norm — creating the institutional/legal power to regulate landlords. I'll treat it as a competence norm since the focus is on establishing a legal basis for a licensing system.\n\n**Step 3: promulgation**\nThe letter is from the Minister of the Interior (BZK) — the reference to "de Minister van SZW namens mij" suggests this is the Minister of BZK (Kajsa Ollongren was Minister of BZK in 2021, responsible for housing). The document is from 2021, Kamerstuk 27 926.\n\n**Step 4: scope**\nRental housing market in the Netherlands; municipal enforcement against malicious landlords.\n\n**Step 5: conditions**\nThe legal basis is described as "mogelijke" (possible) — it is exploratory/advisory at this stage.\n\n**Step 6: subject**\nMunicipalities (gemeenten) and landlords (verhuurders) — the licensing system would apply to landlords, enforced by municipalities.\n\n**Step 7: legal_modality**\n"Can" — the text describes enabling a possible legal basis (competence/permission), not an obligation. The word "mogelijke" (possible) reinforces this.\n\n**Step 8: act_identifier**\nNo specific act is named yet. The Woningwet is referenced for the existing beheerovername instrument, but the new legal basis is unnamed.\n\n**Step 9: signal_certainty**\n"Advisory" — the text describes insights from pilots and exploration of a possible legal basis. No formal proposal has been announced; this is a policy intent/ambition stage.\n\n**Step 10: source_type**\n"Policy_intent" — this is a policy letter reporting on pilots and signalling a possible future statutory instrument, without a concrete bill or formal proposal.\n\n```json\n{\n  "signal_summary": "Insights from municipal pilots on tackling malicious landlords are being used to explore a possible statutory legal basis for a national landlord licensing system, which could enable municipalities to require landlords to hold a permit.",\n  "signal_certainty": "advisory",\n  "source_type": "policy_intent",\n  "norm_identifier": "signal-verhuurdervergunning-wettelijke-grondslag-2021",\n  "norm_type": "competence",\n  "promulgation": "Ministe